   <pb facs="6"/>
   <head>The Preface.</head>
   <p>
      <seg rend="decorInit">I</seg>T is my in<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>tent
to make
triall if by the
waie of cer<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>teine
princi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ples,
there may anie pre<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>cepts
be established, for the
instruction and institution
of a woorthy Courtier: Not
to shew what vertues be<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>long
vnto him, but, presup<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>posing
him alreadie to haue
that habit, which the Court
requireth, to teach him in
what maner he should car<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>ry
himselfe to run the course
of his seruice with happi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>nesse.
<pb facs="7"/>
And because multi<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>plicitie
of words is toilsome
to the writer, and breedes
confusion in the Readers
mind, I wil make my proof<gap reason="illegible: in gutter" extent="1 letter">
         <desc>•</desc>
      </gap>
with that breuitie, which
may exclude obscuritie in
the vnderstanding, and
yet lie very plaine vn<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>to
indifferent ca<g ref="char:EOLhyphen"/>pacities.</p>
